'''Anne de La Vigne''' (1634&ndash;1684) was a French poet and [[Natural philosophy|natural philosopher]] who was a follower of [[René Descartes]]. == Life == She was born in [[Vernon, Eure|Vernon, Normandy]]<nowiki/>in 1634. Her father was the French physician [[Michel de La Vigne|Michel de La Vigne. She]] died in [[Paris]] at the age of 50.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science: L-Z|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=LTSYePZvSXYC|publisher = Taylor & Francis|date = 2000-01-01|isbn = 9780415920407|language = en|first = Marilyn Bailey|last = Ogilvie|first2 = Joy Dorothy|last2 = Harvey}}</ref> She was a friend of [[Mademoiselle de Scuderi]] and [[Marie Dapre]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:A_cyclopaedia_of_female_biography.djvu/779|title=A cyclopaedia of female biography|last=|first=|date=|website=en.wikisource.org|page=779|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-11-15|chapter=VIGNE, ANNE DE LA}}</ref>
== Works == *''Ode sur les conquestes du Roy'', Paris, S. Mabre-Cramoisy, 1673 *''Les Dames à Mlle de Scudéry'', ode, Paris, 1672 *"Quelques poèmes" in ''Chefs-d'œuvre poétiques des dames françaises''.
