[[File:FOTO RITRATTO DI CLAUDIO PIZZI.jpg|thumb]]
'''Claudio E.A. Pizzi''' (born 20 September 1944, [[Milan]]) is an Italian [[logician]] and [[epistemologist]].

== Biography ==
Pizzi completed his Master's degree in philosophy from the [[State University of Milan]] in 1969. From 1976, he taught [[Philosophy of logic|logic]] for three years at the [[University of Calabria]]. He then worked as a professor of logic and of [[philosophy of science]] at the [[University of Siena]] from 1979 to 2014, in which he became a [[full professor]] in 1997. Beginning from 1992, he worked for several Brazilian universities and especially for Centro de Logica, Epistemologia e Historia da Ciencia (CLE) of the [[University of Campinas]]. From 2008-2012, he taught logic of proof at the Faculty of Law of the second State University of Milan.<ref name="MagnaniCarnielli2010">{{cite book|last1=Magnani|first1=Lorenzo|last2=Carnielli|first2=Walter|editor1= Lorenzo Magnani|editor2=Walter Carnielli|editor3=Claudio Pizzi|title=Model-Based Reasoning in Science and Technology: Abduction, Logic, and Computational Discovery|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W8JgZUoEWC8C&pg=PRXI|year=2010|publisher=Springer|location=Berlin|isbn=978-3-642-15222-1|pages=xi–xvi|chapter=Years of Reasoning: In Honor of the 65th Birthday of Claudio Pizzi}}</ref>

== Research activities ==
After completing his studies, Pizzi edited the Italian translation of G.E. Hughes and M.J. Cresswell's ''An Introduction to [[Modal logic|Modal Logic]]''<ref>{{cite book|first1=G.E. |last1=Hughes|first2=M.J.|last2=Cresswell|title=Introduzione alla logica modale|publisher=Il Saggiatore|location=milano|year=1968|translator-first=Claudio E.A.|translator-last=Pizzi}}</ref> and published two anthologies in 1974 and 1979 aimed to spread the knowledge of two areas of intensional logic unknown in Italy: [[tense logic]]<ref>{{cite book|title=La logica del tempo|editor-first=Claudio E.A.|editor-last=Pizzi|publisher=Boringhieri|location=Torino|year=1974}}</ref> and [[conditional logic]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Leggi di natura, modalità, ipotesi|editor-first=Claudio E.A.|editor-last=Pizzi|publisher=Feltrinelli|location=Milano|year=1979}}</ref> In a number of academic papers, he developed a variant of so-called [[connexive logic]] named "logic of consequential implication",<ref>{{cite SEP|url-id =logic-connexive|title=Connexive Logic|first=Heinrich|last=Wansing|date=8 August 2014}}</ref> which turns out to be translatable in the main system of propositional modal logic and so decidable via the ''[[TABLEAUX|tableaux]]'' method.<ref>{{cite book|editor=M. D’Agostino|title=Handbook of Tableau Methods|publisher=Kluwer Academic Publishers|year=1999}}</ref>

Pizzi is also known for his contributions to modal logic concerning the problem of defining [[Necessity and sufficiency|necessity]] in terms of contingency<ref>{{cite journal|first=Claudio E.A.|last=Pizzi|title=Necessity and Relative Contingency|journal=Studia Logica|year=2007|volume=85|pages=305-410}}</ref> and the use of Aristotelian squares and cubes in visualizing the relations between modal notions.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Claudio E.A.|last=Pizzi|title=Generalization and Composition of Modal Squares of Opposition|journal=Logica Universalis|year=2016|volume=26|pages=1-13}}</ref> In collaboration with Brazilian logicians, Pizzi has explored the subject of multimodal logics (i.e. of logics whose language has more than one modal primitive), to which he produced a monograph.<ref>{{cite book|first=Claudio E.A.|last=Pizzi|first2=W.|last2=Carnielli|title=Modalities and Multimodalities|publisher=Springer|location=New York|year=2008}}</ref> His last book (2017) contains a methodological  analysis of the investigations about a plane crash which took place in 1980, known as the "Ustica massacre".

