'''Gerald Glynn O'Collins''' [[Order of Australia|AC]] [[Society of Jesus|SJ]] is an Australian [[Jesuit]] [[priesthood (Catholic Church)|priest]], author, academic and educator.<ref>Cf. academic record and bio-bibliographical details on [http://www.mn.catholic.org.au/newsroom/pdf/Jesus%20the%20Christ%20EConference%20Speaker%20Biographies.pdf Academic Staff Archive] of the [http://www.mn.catholic.org.au/ Diocese of Maitland-Newcastle's official website].</ref> He is currently a research professor and writer-in-residence at the Jesuit Theological College (JTC) in [[Parkville, Victoria]], and a research professor in theology at [[St Mary's University College, Twickenham|St Mary's University College]] in [[Twickenham]].<ref>Biographical sources extracted from the [http://gazettes.ag.gov.au/portal/govgazonline.nsf/1F6AF5C00FA79412CA257101007EA685/$file/S%201.pdf Australian Government Gazette of 26 January 2006, pp.1–2].</ref> For more than three decades, he was professor of systematic and fundamental theology at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] (Rome).<ref>Cf. ACU biography at [http://www.acu.edu.au/about_acu/faculties_schools_institutes_centres/faculties/theology_and_philosophy/the_public_square/conferences/special_occasion_conferences_organised_by_the_faculty/vatican_ii_symposium/keynote_speakers/rev._professor_gerald_ocollins_sj_ac Australian Catholic University, Faculty]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}; [http://humbleapproach.templeton.org/incarnate/GeraldOCollins.html HAI Symposium]; [http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/101260.Gerald_O_Collins GoodReads Biography].</ref>

In 2006, O'Collins was made a Companion of the General Division of the [[Order of Australia]] (AC), in recognition of his outstanding commitment to theological scholarship and ecumenical initiatives.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1131291&search_type=simple&showInd=true Australian Government: Australian Honours 2006].</ref>
{{Jesuit}}

==Life and career==
O'Collins was born in [[Melbourne]], Australia, in 1931. His maternal grandfather [[Paddy Glynn]] was a federal government minister, while his sister [[Maev O'Collins]] became a professor at the [[University of Papua New Guinea]]. O'Collins studied at the [[University of Melbourne]], where he took both a first-class honours [[baccalaureate degree]] and a master's degree. He was ordained a [[Roman Catholic priest]] in 1963 and went on to earn a [[Licentiate in Sacred Theology]] (STL) at [[Heythrop College]], London, in 1967. The next year he was made a [[Doctor of Theology]] by [[Cambridge University]], where he held a research [[Graduate school fellowship|fellowship]] at [[Pembroke College, Cambridge|Pembroke College]]. He taught at the Weston School of Theology ([[Boston Theological Institute]]) in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], and the JTC in Melbourne for five years before accepting a professorship at the [[Gregorian University]] in Rome in 1973. He taught there until 2006. Additionally, he served as [[Dean (academic)|dean]] of the theological faculty for six years. After retiring from the Gregorian he was named research professor at St. Mary's University College.<ref>Cf. information on [http://www.acu.edu.au/about_acu/faculties_schools_institutes_centres/faculties/theology_and_philosophy/the_public_square/conferences/special_occasion_conferences_organised_by_the_faculty/vatican_ii_symposium/keynote_speakers/rev._professor_gerald_ocollins_sj_ac "Rev. Professor Gerald O'Collins SJ AC"]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Australian Catholic University]], [[Melbourne]].</ref>

O'Collins's has received several honorary doctorates:<ref>As also listed by [https://wipfandstock.com/author/15785 WIPF & STOCK] Accessed 25 October 2012</ref> from the [[University of San Francisco]] (1991), [[University of Surrey]] (2003), [[Sacred Heart University]] (Bridgeport, Conn.) (2004); [[John Carroll University]] (Cleveland, Ohio) (2007); and a DD from [[Melbourne College of Divinity]] (2007); Honorary adjunct professor of [[Australian Catholic University]] (2007–2010).<ref>Cf. O'Collins' CV on [[St. Mary's University College (Twickenham)]] [http://www.smuc.ac.uk/tph/staff/research/Prof-Gerald-O'Collins-SJ.pdf website].</ref>

O'Collins organised and co-chaired international ecumenical symposia on the [[Resurrection]] (1996), the [[Trinity]] (1998), the [[Incarnation]] (2000), the [[Redemption (theology)|Redemption]] (2003), and the legacy of [[Pope John Paul II]] (2008), also co-editing their proceedings.<ref>Cf. biographical details on [http://humbleapproach.templeton.org/incarnate/GeraldOCollins.html ''Humble Approach Initiative''], August 2011 Symposium.</ref> He returned to Australia in 2009.

O'Collins has been an honorary visitor and a visiting scholar at Pembroke College, and he currently serves as an honorary adjunct professor at the [[Australian Catholic University]]. He has delivered the Fisher Lecture and the [[Margaret Beaufort, Countess of Richmond and Derby|Margaret Beaufort]] Lecture at [[Cambridge]] and the [[Cardinal Hume]] Lectures at Heythrop College. Amongst other honours, he is the recipient of the Malipiero Prize, the [[Stefano Borgia]] European Prize, and the [[Johannes Quasten]] Medal given by [[Catholic University of America]].<ref>See Australian Government websites, as listed on [http://agencysearch.australia.gov.au/search/search.cgi?collection=agencies&profile=pmc_honour&query=gerald+%22O+COLLINS%22&scope_disable=on "ABC Broadcasting Personalities"] Accessed 25 October 2012</ref>

