{{Infobox philosopher | name = Mary Dietz | region = [[American philosophy|American]] | era = [[Contemporary philosophy]] | image = | image_size = | caption = | fullname = Mary Golden Dietz | birth_date = {{abbr|c.|circa}} {{birth year and age|1950}} | birth_place = | death_date = | school_tradition = | main_interests = [[Political philosophy]], [[Feminist theory]], [[History of philosophy]] | notable_ideas = | institutions = | influences = | influenced = | signature = }}
'''Mary Golden Dietz''' (born {{abbr|c.|circa}} 1950) is the John Evans Professor of Political Theory at [[Northwestern University]].<ref name="Northwestern Political Science Dept.">{{cite web|url=http://www.polisci.northwestern.edu/people/dietz.html|title=Mary G Dietz |publisher=Weinberg College of Arts & Sciences, Department of Political Science |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> She holds a joint appointment in Northwestern's Department of Political Science and its Gender and Sexuality Studies Program. She is the author of many books and articles in [[feminist theory]] and the [[history of philosophy]] and edited the journal, ''Political Theory: An International Journal of Political Philosophy'', from 2005-2012. Prior to joining the faculty at Northwestern, she taught at the University of Minnesota.<ref name="Gender Studies Newsletter interview.">{{cite web|title=An Interview with Mary G. Dietz|url=http://www.genderstudies.northwestern.edu/docs/newsletters/GD_Fall07_Newsletter_Final.pdf|accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref>
Dietz graduated ''Magna Cum Laude'' from [[Mount Holyoke College]] in 1972 with a degree in political science.<ref name=CV>{{cite web|last=Dietz|first=Mary|title=Curriculum Vitae|url=http://www.scholars.northwestern.edu/expertAddInfo.asp?n=Mary+Golden+Dietz&u_id=534|accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> Dietz did her master's and doctoral work at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. While there she developed an interest in the work of [[Hannah Arendt]] through graduate seminars with the political theorist [[Hanna Pitkin]].<ref name="Gender Studies Newsletter interview."/>
She is the author of ''Between the Human and the Divine: The Political Thought of Simone Weil'' (1988)<ref>{{cite book|last=Dietz|first=Mary G.|title=Between the human and the divine : the political thought of Simone Weil|year=1988|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Totowa (N.J.)|isbn=0847675750}}</ref> and ''Turning Operations: Feminism, Arendt, Politics'' (2002).<ref>{{cite book|last=Dietz|first=Mary G.|title=Turning operations : feminism, Arendt and politics|year=2002|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=0415932459}}</ref><ref name=Lee>{{cite journal|last=Lee|first=Theresa Man Ling |title=Flank Attacks |journal=The Review of Politics|date=Fall 2004|volume=66|issue=4|pages=699–701|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=5368308|accessdate=February 22, 2014|doi=10.1017/s0034670500040031}}</ref> She is also the editor of ''Thomas Hobbes & Political Theory'' (1990).<ref>{{cite book|last=Dietz|first=edited by Mary G.|title=Thomas Hobbes and political theory|year=1990|publisher=University Press of Kansas|location=Lawrence, Kan.|isbn=0700604200}}</ref> Dietz has also published over 25 articles, 15 book reviews, and 21 chapters during her career.
