{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|20th century Philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Richard H. Kennington''' |birth_date = 1921 |birth_place = [[Worcester, Massachusetts]] |death_date = 1999 |death_place = [[Annapolis, Maryland]] |school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy|Continental]] | institutions = [[Pennsylvania State University]] |main_interests = [[early modern philosophy]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = |notable_ideas = | spouse = Pamela Kraus | education = | alma_mater = [[The New School for Social Research]], [[University of California]] |influences = [[Descartes]], [[Heidegger]], [[Husserl]], [[Hans Jonas]], [[Leo Strauss]] |influenced = [[Richard Velkley]] |awards = }}
'''Richard H. Kennington''' (1921 in [[Worcester, Massachusetts]] - September 10, 1999 in [[Annapolis, Maryland]]) was an American philosopher and professor of [[philosophy]] at [[Pennsylvania State University]] and the [[Catholic University of America]]. He is known for his research on [[early modern philosophy]] and his translation of Descartes' ''[[Discourse on the Method]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Masters and Possessors of Nature|url=https://www.thenewatlantis.com/publications/masters-and-possessors-of-nature|website=[[The New Atlantis (journal)|The New Atlantis]]|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=First Principles - Masks of Mastery: Richard Kennington on Modern Origins|url=http://www.firstprinciplesjournal.com/print.aspx?article=1594|website=First Principles|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Anstey|first1=Peter|title=Masters of Nature|journal=[[Metascience (journal)|Metascience]]|date=1 March 2006|volume=15|issue=1|pages=137–140|doi=10.1007/s11016-006-0006-1|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11016-006-0006-1|accessdate=31 January 2018|language=en|issn=0815-0796}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Richard H. Kennington (1921–1999): A Remembrance|url=https://home.isi.org/richard-h-kennington-1921%E2%80%931999-remembrance|website=[[Political Science Reviewer]]|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ESSAYS IN HONOR OF RICHARD KENNINGTON|url=http://blogs.newschool.edu/graduate-faculty-philosophy-journal/category/11-20/112-essays-in-honor-of-richard-kennington/|website=Graduate Faculty Philosophy Journal|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>
